WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.520
RICHARD: I don't think. since we started this business.

2
00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:06.000
we've had a proper American muscle car in.

3
00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:08.760
That is an unbelievable racket.

4
00:00:10.120 --> 00:00:12.480
You can't beat building someone's car

5
00:00:12.560 --> 00:00:16.520
and being the first person to drive it. It's a great feeling.

6
00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:20.000
Oh. I think I've spoken too soon.

7
00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:21.880
I think that was a misfire.

8
00:00:21.960 --> 00:00:25.040
If you want this. you've either gotta put more in it

9
00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:30.080
and make it work. or call it a day.

10
00:00:30.160 --> 00:00:33.160
After four rollercoaster years

11
00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:35.120
in the classic car restoration business...

12
00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:37.600
That worked. I'm gonna claim I thought of everything.

13
00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:39.840
...it seems I've finally cracked it.

14
00:00:39.920 --> 00:00:42.400
Happy customer. That's a good feeling.

15
00:00:42.480 --> 00:00:44.480
We've dragged our PR department...

16
00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:47.040
You've gotta get your arses over here damn quick.

17
00:00:47.120 --> 00:00:49.600
...into the 21st century.

18
00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:53.400
Our reach on that day was 317.000 people.

19
00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:55.120
And as brand ambassador...

20
00:00:56.120 --> 00:00:58.280
If you happen to have a car in the UK ever...

21
00:00:58.360 --> 00:01:00.280
...I'm leading the charge.

22
00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:02.920
Hey. hey! This is brilliant!

23
00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:05.400
At least that's what I thought...

24
00:01:05.480 --> 00:01:09.680
If you've overpromised... Yeah. ...you can't under-deliver.

25
00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:12.000
...until my mum arrived.

26
00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:14.240
They won't listen to me. They'll listen to me.

27
00:01:14.320 --> 00:01:17.400
And it turns out that. once again. I'm in deep trouble.

28
00:01:18.520 --> 00:01:20.680
I'm gonna have to do something. Something big.

29
00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:22.360
Oh. my God!

30
00:01:43.480 --> 00:01:45.920
I'm still grappling with this conundrum

31
00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:48.880
Hadrian's given me. which is. basically.

32
00:01:48.960 --> 00:01:51.200
we're not making any money.

33
00:01:51.280 --> 00:01:53.280
But we're not gonna make any more money

34
00:01:53.360 --> 00:01:58.360
until we employ more staff. which means spending more money.

35
00:01:58.440 --> 00:02:00.040
It's very confusing.

36
00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:02.040
I'm not playing with this.

37
00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:04.240
I'm thinking about American cars

38
00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:07.200
because following the Malibu restoration we did.

39
00:02:07.280 --> 00:02:08.880
which went rather well.

40
00:02:08.960 --> 00:02:11.640
we have another American vehicle coming in for some work.

41
00:02:11.720 --> 00:02:14.680
And Jamie tells me that. well. the job's great

42
00:02:14.760 --> 00:02:18.880
because it's just bodywork and paint. no mechanical.

43
00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:21.960
which is perfect. Exciting.

44
00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:30.400
Jamie. he's here.

45
00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:33.600
JAMIE: Oh. wow. That's bigger than I thought.

46
00:02:33.680 --> 00:02:36.520
Yeah. yeah. that's a lot of truck. RICH: How you doing?

47
00:02:36.600 --> 00:02:38.240
Very well. Nice to meet you. And you.

48
00:02:38.320 --> 00:02:41.240
Why have you got this? You've got a truck. you pulled in with it.

49
00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:43.520
I just wanted to take it around the shows.

50
00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:45.680
Oh. this is to be shown? Yeah. yeah. yeah.

51
00:02:45.760 --> 00:02:47.720
Okay. it's not there yet. is it? No. no. no!

52
00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:49.440
It's no good taking it like it is.

53
00:02:49.520 --> 00:02:51.600
I don't know where it came from in America.

54
00:02:51.680 --> 00:02:53.560
It came from a good... It was dry.

55
00:02:53.640 --> 00:02:56.560
Yeah. yeah. That's California or somewhere. That's amazing.

56
00:02:56.640 --> 00:02:59.000
So. mechanically. you're happy? Yes.

57
00:02:59.080 --> 00:03:00.680
So it's just body... Body work.

58
00:03:00.760 --> 00:03:03.760
And you want this as a show car? Yes.

59
00:03:03.840 --> 00:03:05.440
So. proper... Proper job.

60
00:03:05.520 --> 00:03:08.880
Look at that tailgate. Gorgeous. isn't it? I'd rather keep the tailgate

61
00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:12.360
to show that it's been a working vehicle. I couldn't agree more.

62
00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:15.000
I quite like the idea of having it lacquered. Yeah.

63
00:03:15.080 --> 00:03:17.920
It'll protect it. I'll matte-lacquer it. You don't want gloss.

64
00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:20.600
So it'll look like this. but it won't deteriorate or rust.

65
00:03:20.680 --> 00:03:23.840
It's frozen in time. It's literally a time machine. Yeah. yeah.

66
00:03:23.920 --> 00:03:26.320
So. originally. you were gonna do this yourself? Yes.

67
00:03:26.400 --> 00:03:28.800
Well. I had a stroke just after I bought it.

68
00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:30.880
So many things are wrong with me now. look.

69
00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:32.720
but. you know. I'm happy enough.

70
00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:34.800
Yeah. well. you got a truck.

71
00:03:34.880 --> 00:03:38.720
I got two! How bad can life be?

72
00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:41.960
Big question. colour for the rest of the truck?

73
00:03:42.040 --> 00:03:44.720
I don't know what colour I wanna have it yet.

74
00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:46.880
Should we look up some colours? Yes. please.

75
00:03:46.960 --> 00:03:48.960
Can we come to a show? Of course. any show.

76
00:03:49.040 --> 00:03:53.240
Exciting. Right. well. if we're good to go... Yes.

77
00:03:53.320 --> 00:03:56.360
Good. Good. We'll take it on. Looking forward to it.

78
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:00.040
They're not making these things any more.

79
00:04:00.120 --> 00:04:03.040
And it goes on the scrap heap. it's gone. finished.

80
00:04:03.120 --> 00:04:05.960
If I can get another 50 years out of it. 60 years out of it.

81
00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:09.120
when I'm gone. somebody else can have it and look after it.

82
00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:10.800
And that's why I'm doing it.

83
00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:12.760
We'll get it off the trailer for you.

84
00:04:12.840 --> 00:04:17.240
If you can move your big truck. somebody else in Herefordshire can park here. Like. everybody.

85
00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:19.480
'Cause it's massive.

86
00:04:20.280 --> 00:04:21.880
I really like that truck.

87
00:04:21.960 --> 00:04:24.560
I'm also really pleased that Richard decided to leave

88
00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:26.680
the tailgate patinated.

89
00:04:26.760 --> 00:04:28.720
'cause that is the truck's story

90
00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:31.480
there to see. and it's a story of work.

91
00:04:31.560 --> 00:04:33.520
Back in the '50s. when that truck was new.

92
00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:35.760
I suppose our working vehicles were Land Rovers.

93
00:04:35.840 --> 00:04:38.120
Over there. the equivalent is still the pickup.

94
00:04:38.200 --> 00:04:39.840
People love 'em. They drive them

95
00:04:39.920 --> 00:04:42.960
even if they don't need a pickup. 'cause they're cool.

96
00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:46.000
And that. that's one of the originals.

97
00:04:46.080 --> 00:04:48.640
I wanna see that truck at a show.

98
00:04:48.720 --> 00:04:51.200
Rich. as the owner. is gonna love that.

99
00:04:51.280 --> 00:04:54.520
I've said it now. it's gonna happen.

100
00:04:56.080 --> 00:04:59.280
The only problem is. that's a lot of truck.

101
00:04:59.360 --> 00:05:02.920
And currently. Jamie's the only one who can do the bodywork.

102
00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:04.640
prep. and paint.

103
00:05:04.720 --> 00:05:07.800
which points to the big issue that Hadrian's highlighted.

104
00:05:07.880 --> 00:05:11.400
we desperately need more staff.

105
00:05:21.960 --> 00:05:28.080
There is no doubt I need more hands at The Smallest Cog.

106
00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:30.640
So. through Hadrian. he's helped me get a hold of

107
00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:32.720
a human resources consultant.

108
00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:36.400
And I've come to London to meet him. Let's see if I can make a plan.

109
00:05:39.160 --> 00:05:40.760
Thank you.

110
00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:54.720
Wayne. hi. Nice to meet you. Richard. Nice to meet you.

111
00:05:54.800 --> 00:05:56.400
Have a seat. Thank you.

112
00:05:56.480 --> 00:05:59.240
And thanks for agreeing to the meeting. I've booked a corner

113
00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:01.120
in the library. but we can't...

114
00:06:03.480 --> 00:06:06.080
Sorry. that was a mistake. I didn't think that through.

115
00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:09.840
Broadly. what I am is a classic car restoration business. and that's your area.

116
00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:12.120
Yeah. we look after a number of workshops.

117
00:06:12.200 --> 00:06:14.400
Okay. So what bits can you help with?

118
00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:17.560
Have you had a think about what type of roles you're looking for?

119
00:06:17.640 --> 00:06:20.720
Roles-wise. I need another mechanic.

120
00:06:20.800 --> 00:06:22.800
Possibly another two mechanics. Okay.

121
00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:24.600
I need another painter.

122
00:06:24.680 --> 00:06:29.800
But if all of them or some of them can also prepare.

123
00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:32.160
can fabricate. can weld. Okay.

124
00:06:32.240 --> 00:06:35.600
And the guys you have in the workshop... Yeah.

125
00:06:35.680 --> 00:06:37.280
...where did you find them?

126
00:06:37.360 --> 00:06:40.440
In a skip. Okay. We can do this.

127
00:06:40.520 --> 00:06:46.840
We have a real opportunity to share this story with the world

128
00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:48.880
through social media. first and foremost.

129
00:06:48.960 --> 00:06:50.760
So let's tell everybody

130
00:06:50.840 --> 00:06:53.200
that you are looking to recruit new people.

131
00:06:53.280 --> 00:06:55.520
We'll interview them the first time.

132
00:06:55.600 --> 00:06:57.760
And then the second time. we'll bring them in.

133
00:06:57.840 --> 00:06:59.640
That's when you can give 'em a grilling.

134
00:06:59.720 --> 00:07:03.440
Your hardest decision. by the time we get to that final stage.

135
00:07:03.520 --> 00:07:06.480
is which one not to take... Mm-hm. ...not which one to take.

136
00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:09.680
Wow. that's... That's a good line. I like that.

137
00:07:11.800 --> 00:07:14.440
He seems quite human for an HR consultant.

138
00:07:14.520 --> 00:07:17.280
I was surprised because I'm very conscious.

139
00:07:17.360 --> 00:07:19.680
We're talking about people's jobs.

140
00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:22.720
Somebody joins us. it's not a pipe dream.

141
00:07:22.800 --> 00:07:24.640
it's not a game. it's their livelihood.

142
00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:28.120
Depending on how many we employ.

143
00:07:28.200 --> 00:07:32.560
we could be looking at upwards of another 100K in new salaries.

144
00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:35.960
The pressure to win more work just got bigger.

145
00:07:55.800 --> 00:07:59.520
Jamie. Jamie! Oh.

146
00:07:59.600 --> 00:08:01.200
Yeah? Hello.

147
00:08:01.280 --> 00:08:04.200
I've just come off the phone with Rich. owner of the F-100.

148
00:08:04.280 --> 00:08:07.320
Yeah. And. you know. he wanted to get it into a show.

149
00:08:07.400 --> 00:08:09.600
He's found one. When is it?

150
00:08:09.680 --> 00:08:13.360
It's the week after next. and he's booked it into the competition to be judged.

151
00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:16.240
Er. you might wanna come and have a look at this. then.

152
00:08:16.320 --> 00:08:19.120
Right. Is this good or bad? Bad.

153
00:08:21.320 --> 00:08:23.960
I can see an issue. yes.

154
00:08:24.040 --> 00:08:26.080
The door's not the best. to be honest.

155
00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:28.000
'cause it's rotted from the inside out.

156
00:08:28.080 --> 00:08:30.880
Oh. that really has gone. Yeah.

157
00:08:30.960 --> 00:08:32.720
Can we repair that in-house?

158
00:08:32.800 --> 00:08:35.240
The problem we've got is we haven't got the workforce.

159
00:08:35.320 --> 00:08:37.600
Everybody's busy on other stuff. Yeah.

160
00:08:37.680 --> 00:08:39.720
Ooh. Isaac is coming up with a plan.

161
00:08:39.800 --> 00:08:41.880
I'd like to hear the results of this thinking.

162
00:08:41.960 --> 00:08:44.560
Isaac. have you got a minute? Yep.

163
00:08:44.640 --> 00:08:46.240
Erm... Hello.

164
00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:49.880
There are rumours of you having been involved in thinking.

165
00:08:49.960 --> 00:08:52.960
I know. it's the second time.

166
00:08:53.040 --> 00:08:56.600
So. Dan from over there. he can do all of this.

167
00:08:56.680 --> 00:08:59.240
What. Dan from Hadrian's place? HMS. yeah.

168
00:08:59.320 --> 00:09:01.240
I've already called him. He's on his way?

169
00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:04.440
Yeah. This is a whole new thing. I've been presented with problem

170
00:09:04.520 --> 00:09:06.680
and solution. I like it.

171
00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:15.720
We know Dan. we know his work's good.

172
00:09:15.800 --> 00:09:17.680
and it's great that we can bring him in.

173
00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:20.080
But it does kind of highlight that we are a bit

174
00:09:20.160 --> 00:09:23.960
short on skills and staff.

175
00:09:24.040 --> 00:09:26.640
We're gonna have to do something about it.

176
00:09:26.720 --> 00:09:28.360
We've got to bite the bullet.

177
00:09:28.440 --> 00:09:30.040
It's an expensive bullet.

178
00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:39.160
It didn't used to be this complicated.

179
00:09:39.240 --> 00:09:43.360
There are moments when I can't help hankering after simpler times.

180
00:09:43.440 --> 00:09:45.600
Here's a key fact.

181
00:09:45.680 --> 00:09:48.200
it's Friday and I have fish and chips.

182
00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:50.040
It's fish-and-chip Friday.

183
00:09:52.240 --> 00:09:55.440
I'm off to visit Neil at his new workshop at home.

184
00:09:55.520 --> 00:09:57.680
and I'm travelling in this Jaguar.

185
00:09:57.760 --> 00:10:00.320
which is the car that started all this.

186
00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:03.560
He restored this for me years ago. And just like the old days.

187
00:10:03.640 --> 00:10:06.560
I've got a slight favour to ask him while I'm there.

188
00:10:20.480 --> 00:10:22.080
Shop!

189
00:10:23.040 --> 00:10:26.240
Hello. All right. mate. Now. it's Friday.

190
00:10:26.320 --> 00:10:27.920
It is. It's lunchtime.

191
00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:29.840
It is. For old time's sake...

192
00:10:29.920 --> 00:10:32.280
Oh. ...fish-and-chip Friday. There it is.

193
00:10:32.360 --> 00:10:34.080
Really? Wow. But it gets even better.

194
00:10:34.160 --> 00:10:36.680
Not only have I brought you fish and chips for lunch.

195
00:10:36.760 --> 00:10:39.840
but I've brought you a little challenge that you'll just love. Yeah.

196
00:10:39.920 --> 00:10:42.280
Because you... Come and have a look.

197
00:10:42.360 --> 00:10:44.840
You're saying there's no such thing as a free lunch?

198
00:10:44.920 --> 00:10:46.720
That's exactly it. yes.

199
00:10:46.800 --> 00:10:48.400
This is a real treat.

200
00:10:48.480 --> 00:10:51.440
The check strap's gone on this door. so it flies open.

201
00:10:51.520 --> 00:10:54.360
How did you manage to do that? It just sort of broke.

202
00:10:54.440 --> 00:10:56.560
It's a metal one. I think. isn't it? Oh. yeah.

203
00:10:56.640 --> 00:10:59.240
'Cause usually. they're cloth. I'll put your chips inside.

204
00:10:59.320 --> 00:11:02.400
Yeah. And I'll come out and help. They'll be there waiting.

205
00:11:02.480 --> 00:11:04.520
All right. there we go. Ah!

206
00:11:04.600 --> 00:11:07.280
Boys and their toys. what's he done with this?

207
00:11:07.360 --> 00:11:09.920
Right. this is your problem. Check strap's snapped.

208
00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.320
It's pulled that piece out. The eye. It's broken.

209
00:11:12.400 --> 00:11:14.280
Yes. it's pulled it out. That's gone bing.

210
00:11:14.360 --> 00:11:17.840
That piece is missing. So what we'll have to do is remake that eye.

211
00:11:17.920 --> 00:11:19.880
Can you do it before fish and chips go cold?

212
00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:22.960
Hopefully. fingers crossed. Right. We don't like cold chips. No.

213
00:11:23.040 --> 00:11:25.520
We'll need a washer. just the right size. Yeah. or two.

214
00:11:25.600 --> 00:11:27.720
And a welder. And a minute. Or two. or three.

215
00:11:33.360 --> 00:11:35.320
Drill's died. Now's not the time to run out.

216
00:11:36.040 --> 00:11:39.720
You'll be glad to know that I'm only £143 an hour.

217
00:11:39.800 --> 00:11:41.480
So... That's good.

218
00:11:41.560 --> 00:11:43.800
But the chips were quite expensive.

219
00:11:43.880 --> 00:11:46.080
I thought they might be.

220
00:11:46.160 --> 00:11:49.320
We can either cut that lug off. weld that to the end.

221
00:11:49.400 --> 00:11:52.400
grind it round. so it's flat. and she'll look just the job.

222
00:11:52.480 --> 00:11:54.080
Stick her back in. job done.

223
00:11:54.160 --> 00:11:56.520
That needs a bit of planning. I feel famished now.

224
00:11:56.600 --> 00:11:58.320
Calorific intake is what's demanded.

225
00:11:58.400 --> 00:12:00.600
Chips. then welding. You'll lose concentration.

226
00:12:00.680 --> 00:12:02.480
It could be dangerous.

227
00:12:04.360 --> 00:12:07.600
Well. sitting here eating fish and chips next to that jab...

228
00:12:07.680 --> 00:12:09.960
Yeah. ...is very familiar.

229
00:12:10.040 --> 00:12:12.680
I remember when you rang me.

230
00:12:12.760 --> 00:12:15.200
and you'd cut it in half. Yeah. I remember that.

231
00:12:15.280 --> 00:12:18.000
I remember. I came back thinking. "Oh. it'll be in paint."

232
00:12:18.080 --> 00:12:20.120
And you'd literally taken the side off it.

233
00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:23.040
but no. it was bugging me. I knew there was something wrong.

234
00:12:24.800 --> 00:12:28.360
I reckon we'd better go and do the check strap.

235
00:12:28.440 --> 00:12:32.440
Yeah. Otherwise. we're gonna want a nap. Yeah.

236
00:12:42.600 --> 00:12:45.680
This is like old times. It really is.

237
00:12:45.760 --> 00:12:48.400
Watching Neil work and being creative

238
00:12:48.480 --> 00:12:50.560
without the pressure of having to do things

239
00:12:50.640 --> 00:12:53.680
within a certain amount of time. it's cottage. but it's lovely.

240
00:12:53.760 --> 00:12:56.680
Might do more fish-and-chip Fridays to sneak out. to escape.

241
00:12:56.760 --> 00:12:58.360
for old time's sake.

242
00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:02.560
Mended by the power of chips.

243
00:13:02.640 --> 00:13:06.720
Ah. just gonna get that in. There.

244
00:13:13.240 --> 00:13:15.080
There we go.

245
00:13:15.160 --> 00:13:17.040
There it is. Right. try that.

246
00:13:17.120 --> 00:13:19.000
It's working. How far does she come out?

247
00:13:19.080 --> 00:13:20.800
Far enough. Look at that. Perfect.

248
00:13:20.880 --> 00:13:23.600
Brilliant. Thanks. Best fish and chips you spent for a while.

249
00:13:23.680 --> 00:13:27.440
I brought you fish and chips. and for pudding. a nice fix.

250
00:13:27.520 --> 00:13:29.160
I thought you meant you got pudding.

251
00:13:29.240 --> 00:13:32.120
I'm gutted now. No. no. that was your pudding.

252
00:13:32.200 --> 00:13:33.800
Mate. thank you very much. Welcome.

253
00:13:33.880 --> 00:13:36.440
Nice to see you. Joy as always. That's it. There you are.

254
00:13:36.520 --> 00:13:39.040
Next time anything drops off. I'll bring fish and chips.

255
00:13:39.120 --> 00:13:41.320
Thank you. Go steady.

256
00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:43.200
I'll see you soon.

257
00:13:43.280 --> 00:13:45.160
Yeah. ta-da.

258
00:13:45.240 --> 00:13:47.240
I'm not gonna go backwards all the way home.

259
00:13:47.320 --> 00:13:51.400
That's it. try not to knock the gate off.

260
00:13:51.480 --> 00:13:55.280
Seeing Neil reminds me why I started this whole venture.

261
00:13:55.360 --> 00:13:59.160
It's all about a love for classic cars. plain and simple.

262
00:13:59.240 --> 00:14:01.440
Must try not to forget that.

263
00:14:10.560 --> 00:14:15.040
If I'm expanding my team. I'll need more work through the door.

264
00:14:15.120 --> 00:14:18.760
So. as brand ambassador. it's my duty to network.

265
00:14:20.400 --> 00:14:24.360
And a brilliant way of networking is going racing.

266
00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:27.040
That's where I'm off today.

267
00:14:27.120 --> 00:14:29.080
My mate. Patrick Blakeney-Edwards.

268
00:14:29.160 --> 00:14:32.720
invited me to a posh track day at Goodwood.

269
00:14:32.800 --> 00:14:35.200
It's been organised by Fiskens.

270
00:14:35.280 --> 00:14:39.000
very high-end dealers in classic race cars. classic cars.

271
00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:42.280
So I can do some ambassadorial work. talking to.

272
00:14:42.360 --> 00:14:44.760
you know. one day. who knows. potential customers?

273
00:14:44.840 --> 00:14:47.320
But Patrick said. "Bring your race kit."

274
00:14:47.400 --> 00:14:50.880
He'll have a couple of cars there and I get some time on track at Goodwood.

275
00:14:52.520 --> 00:14:56.080
Considered by many to be the spiritual home of the classic car.

276
00:14:56.160 --> 00:15:00.520
Goodwood is the perfect place to forge new relationships

277
00:15:00.600 --> 00:15:02.880
and raise the profile of The Smallest Cog.

278
00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:07.480
And today. the who's who of the elite motorsport world

279
00:15:07.560 --> 00:15:09.160
are here.

280
00:15:13.920 --> 00:15:15.720
Morning. chap! PATRICK: Ey up!

281
00:15:15.800 --> 00:15:17.400
Are you gonna be kind?

282
00:15:17.480 --> 00:15:19.680
So we're gonna do it in quite a methodical way

283
00:15:19.760 --> 00:15:23.160
because it's hard on the brain. and you've got a damaged one anyway.

284
00:15:23.240 --> 00:15:25.880
Thank you! So... Yes. I know.

285
00:15:27.400 --> 00:15:31.320
So. today. what I wanna do. which is what he doesn't know.

286
00:15:31.400 --> 00:15:36.400
is have him co-pilot with me at the Silverstone Festival.

287
00:15:36.480 --> 00:15:38.360
So. if at the end of the day.

288
00:15:38.440 --> 00:15:40.640
I feel that he's close enough to my times.

289
00:15:40.720 --> 00:15:42.720
hell. yeah. we're gonna go and do it.

290
00:15:46.600 --> 00:15:48.440
Right. enjoy it while it's this shape.

291
00:15:48.520 --> 00:15:50.400
Joking.

292
00:15:50.480 --> 00:15:54.360
So. Rich. what I really. really want you to try and do on this session

293
00:15:54.440 --> 00:15:56.360
is to focus on preparing the car

294
00:15:56.440 --> 00:15:59.440
on the right part of the circuit for corner entry.

295
00:15:59.520 --> 00:16:02.240
Corner entry's right. you'll go faster through the corner.

296
00:16:02.320 --> 00:16:05.840
You can then start increasing speed. Corner entry it is. Yep.

297
00:16:06.800 --> 00:16:08.400
Ooh. right. that's me away.

298
00:16:13.760 --> 00:16:16.560
Whilst I try to get to grips with the car.

299
00:16:16.640 --> 00:16:19.400
Patrick's team will be recording my track data

300
00:16:19.480 --> 00:16:21.160
to evaluate my improvements.

301
00:16:21.240 --> 00:16:23.560
That's if there are any.

302
00:16:23.640 --> 00:16:26.480
Middle of the road entry. little on the road to the left.

303
00:16:26.560 --> 00:16:28.880
You're a bit too far over to the right.

304
00:16:28.960 --> 00:16:31.360
Too much braking.

305
00:16:31.440 --> 00:16:33.600
You're keeping it a little bit tight. Tight.

306
00:16:33.680 --> 00:16:36.240
Don't destabilise the car.

307
00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:39.840
I want you to focus on where you're turning in.

308
00:16:39.920 --> 00:16:41.920
If you're coming up to a right-hand corner.

309
00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.840
you want to be turning in from the extreme left.

310
00:16:44.920 --> 00:16:47.640
Be gentle with it. don't provoke it.

311
00:16:48.600 --> 00:16:51.640
So this is sort of your wife. not your mistress.

312
00:16:53.760 --> 00:16:56.560
Are we about to say driving a racing car

313
00:16:56.640 --> 00:16:59.920
is like making love to a beautiful woman?

314
00:17:01.120 --> 00:17:03.160
Okay. turn it in. get it rotated.

315
00:17:03.240 --> 00:17:07.080
Clip the apex. Squeeze the power. squeeze the power.

316
00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:10.040
Exit middle of the road. and then let the car now drift.

317
00:17:10.120 --> 00:17:13.120
Don't hold it. Good.

318
00:17:13.200 --> 00:17:16.360
This is getting better. Perfect!

319
00:17:16.440 --> 00:17:18.640
It's starting to come together.

320
00:17:18.720 --> 00:17:22.920
and your lap times will be coming down by huge amounts.

321
00:17:30.280 --> 00:17:33.920
Yours is quite sporadic. it's almost like you're on the brake. then off the brake.

322
00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:37.280
Yeah. this is the one that I never quite got right.

323
00:17:37.360 --> 00:17:40.440
It's so intimidating 'cause you're coming into it at... Yeah.

324
00:17:40.520 --> 00:17:42.600
...117 kilometres. 117 kilometres. yeah.

325
00:17:42.680 --> 00:17:44.560
You stay on the brakes for longer.

326
00:17:44.640 --> 00:17:47.120
so you're just able to carry more speed through here.

327
00:17:47.880 --> 00:17:50.200
Yes. another ten kilometres an hour. Yeah.

328
00:17:50.280 --> 00:17:52.960
That obviously. you... This is... This is all right.

329
00:17:53.040 --> 00:17:55.240
We are definitely going in the right direction.

330
00:18:04.480 --> 00:18:06.080
So. it's Saturday morning.

331
00:18:06.160 --> 00:18:08.160
It's my day off. but I've decided to come in.

332
00:18:08.240 --> 00:18:11.320
I need to get this F-100 finished for the show next weekend.

333
00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:13.000
so I haven't got much time.

334
00:18:13.080 --> 00:18:15.760
So I've decided to come in and get ahead of the game.

335
00:18:19.600 --> 00:18:23.400
So. owner of the pickup truck has decided to keep the tailgate as it is.

336
00:18:23.480 --> 00:18:26.720
er. so that'll give it a nice patina look.

337
00:18:26.800 --> 00:18:30.120
And at the moment. I'm the only one that can do this job.

338
00:18:30.200 --> 00:18:34.000
We've got interviews next week. So until then. it's down to me.

339
00:18:34.680 --> 00:18:38.000
You can tell how much the owner of this F-100 loves the car.

340
00:18:38.080 --> 00:18:41.160
And to be honest. I've fallen in love with it. as well.

341
00:18:41.240 --> 00:18:46.000
One of my favourites so far. That's what great about this place. you get to work on some awesome cars

342
00:18:46.080 --> 00:18:48.440
and you don't know what's coming through the door.

343
00:18:48.520 --> 00:18:53.080
And I can't wait to get this pickup as good as I can get it.

344
00:18:53.840 --> 00:18:56.040
I'm gonna get in there now and get it painted.

345
00:19:14.160 --> 00:19:16.040
I don't know where you could buy one from.

346
00:19:16.120 --> 00:19:17.800
Cheers. Gregor. how are you?

347
00:19:17.880 --> 00:19:19.800
Having a good day? Absolutely brilliant.

348
00:19:19.880 --> 00:19:22.240
Thank you for inviting me along. It's my pleasure.

349
00:19:22.320 --> 00:19:26.320
Race helmet off. networking hat on.

350
00:19:26.400 --> 00:19:29.600
Today's organiser is a classic car dealer

351
00:19:29.680 --> 00:19:34.080
who's brought with him a cool £50 million worth of stock.

352
00:19:34.160 --> 00:19:39.520
He also has a contacts book full of serious classic car enthusiasts.

353
00:19:39.600 --> 00:19:42.480
The cars are nothing unless they're being used. Yeah.

354
00:19:42.560 --> 00:19:45.800
These are wonderful pieces of art. but as soon as they fire up

355
00:19:45.880 --> 00:19:48.200
and they're brought to their natural environment.

356
00:19:48.280 --> 00:19:50.760
which is Goodwood. it all makes sense.

357
00:19:50.840 --> 00:19:53.280
I've chatted to people in the business here today.

358
00:19:53.360 --> 00:19:56.560
and the people with them are mates. They've known them 20 years. Yeah.

359
00:19:56.640 --> 00:20:00.440
They have a role to play in that friendship. I run a little restoration business.

360
00:20:00.520 --> 00:20:03.400
and what I want to do is. one day. to feel that. you know.

361
00:20:03.480 --> 00:20:06.040
it. I. us can have a little part in that.

362
00:20:06.120 --> 00:20:10.600
It's not a commercial thing. You will. You want to be part of it. You've started. We wanna be in it.

363
00:20:10.680 --> 00:20:13.200
'cause it's a great place to be. Yeah. exactly.

364
00:20:13.280 --> 00:20:15.800
Can I do a bit more driving? We've got a job to do.

365
00:20:15.880 --> 00:20:18.000
We've got about an hour left. Excellent. Enjoy.

366
00:20:18.080 --> 00:20:21.000
Brilliant. Thanks. All right. guys. nice to see you. See you.

367
00:20:24.920 --> 00:20:27.920
Right. I'm going out on my own to see if I can apply

368
00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:31.680
some of what Patrick's been teaching me about the circuit

369
00:20:31.760 --> 00:20:34.640
and the driving. We shall see.

370
00:20:38.160 --> 00:20:41.040
Brake. Braking too much there still.

371
00:20:45.200 --> 00:20:47.800
Don't feather. don't feather. Just brake.

372
00:20:47.880 --> 00:20:51.440
Brake. Brake like you mean it. sure. but brake.

373
00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:55.040
So. that is fast there.

374
00:20:56.640 --> 00:20:58.240
That's better.

375
00:20:58.320 --> 00:21:02.120
I didn't lift. I braked at the 100-metre board. not before.

376
00:21:02.200 --> 00:21:05.000
and that got me in faster. That is faster.

377
00:21:05.080 --> 00:21:06.720
Right.

378
00:21:13.320 --> 00:21:15.120
Nobody needs to know.

379
00:21:21.120 --> 00:21:23.800
Patrick's gonna laugh at me now. Here we go.

380
00:21:23.880 --> 00:21:26.000
Why?

381
00:21:26.080 --> 00:21:27.920
There was a car behind me.

382
00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:31.640
and I was thinking. "I was faster than you last time through here. Oh!

383
00:21:31.720 --> 00:21:33.840
I haven't braked."

384
00:21:33.920 --> 00:21:39.480
So. the good news. though. is you beat your optimum time

385
00:21:39.560 --> 00:21:41.160
to a 144.1.

386
00:21:41.240 --> 00:21:44.520
So. I did every bit on that one lap better than I did...

387
00:21:44.600 --> 00:21:48.000
Yeah. ...every bit on all the laps before. That's encouraging.

388
00:21:48.080 --> 00:21:51.480
That was genuinely. actually. really great. worth doing.

389
00:21:51.560 --> 00:21:55.280
Patrick is a good teacher. actually. I'm never telling him that. ever.

390
00:21:57.280 --> 00:21:59.480
I think you've probably done enough today.

391
00:21:59.560 --> 00:22:03.280
I'm racing this car at Silverstone. Yeah.

392
00:22:03.360 --> 00:22:07.640
The historic festival. proper major headline meeting.

393
00:22:07.720 --> 00:22:10.200
It's an hour-long race. It's two-driver.

394
00:22:10.280 --> 00:22:11.960
Do you want to have a laugh?

395
00:22:12.040 --> 00:22:14.480
So. we'd be sharing the drive?

396
00:22:14.560 --> 00:22:16.200
I'd bloody love to.

397
00:22:16.280 --> 00:22:18.720
You're in? Mate. Brilliant. Yes. I'll do it.

398
00:22:18.800 --> 00:22:21.040
Well. thank you. That's really kind.

399
00:22:21.120 --> 00:22:23.760
That's huge. That's a big event.

400
00:22:23.840 --> 00:22:26.440
It's a huge shop window. potentially. for the business.

401
00:22:26.520 --> 00:22:29.320
because everybody in the classic car world will be there.

402
00:22:29.400 --> 00:22:32.200
But the bigger the opportunity. the bigger the event.

403
00:22:32.280 --> 00:22:34.920
the bigger the chance for me to make a mess of it.

404
00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:39.480
So. if I'm gonna do it. I am gonna have to up my game...

405
00:22:39.560 --> 00:22:41.160
quite a lot.

406
00:23:03.680 --> 00:23:07.080
Rich is here. He's the owner of the Ford pickup truck.

407
00:23:07.160 --> 00:23:08.880
the one that Jamie's loving doing.

408
00:23:08.960 --> 00:23:11.240
We're in a critical stage. He's painted the cream.

409
00:23:11.320 --> 00:23:13.640
that'll be the top half of it. but it's two-tone.

410
00:23:13.720 --> 00:23:15.840
The bottom half needs to be a different colour.

411
00:23:15.920 --> 00:23:19.000
He was over the other day. apparently. and he saw a car of mine.

412
00:23:19.080 --> 00:23:21.840
a Subaru. and loved the colour.

413
00:23:21.920 --> 00:23:24.760
But it's a metallic blue. and I really...

414
00:23:24.840 --> 00:23:28.000
Metallic will not work against that cream.

415
00:23:28.080 --> 00:23:30.160
It'll just...

416
00:23:30.240 --> 00:23:33.000
So. I'm gonna break out my diplomacy.

417
00:23:38.440 --> 00:23:40.520
Hello. Hello. How are you? Good to see you.

418
00:23:40.600 --> 00:23:42.600
Ooh. yes! Steering wheel.

419
00:23:42.680 --> 00:23:47.160
That's lovely. Now. you were talking about a metallic blue.

420
00:23:47.240 --> 00:23:50.120
Yeah. I've got a worry that a metallic

421
00:23:50.200 --> 00:23:54.120
against a flat in a two-tone isn't gonna look right.

422
00:23:54.200 --> 00:23:56.160
What I've got...

423
00:23:56.240 --> 00:24:00.480
A-ha! If you go metallic against a flat.

424
00:24:00.560 --> 00:24:02.200
it starts to look... I know. yeah.

425
00:24:02.280 --> 00:24:03.960
I can see what you're saying. yeah.

426
00:24:04.040 --> 00:24:06.160
What about this one here?

427
00:24:06.240 --> 00:24:07.960
Actually. yeah.

428
00:24:08.040 --> 00:24:10.520
What about that one? JAMIE: Yeah. that would work.

429
00:24:10.600 --> 00:24:13.520
I've just noticed something. What?

430
00:24:13.600 --> 00:24:15.200
Cream and blue.

431
00:24:15.280 --> 00:24:18.840
You're actually your own truck upside down.

432
00:24:18.920 --> 00:24:21.520
If you stand on your hands now. we can have a look at what

433
00:24:21.600 --> 00:24:24.200
it looks like with cream above and blue below.

434
00:24:24.280 --> 00:24:28.080
We will look up a colour that is like the colour on my Subaru

435
00:24:28.160 --> 00:24:30.040
that you saw. but non-metallic. Right.

436
00:24:30.120 --> 00:24:32.720
And there you are. Fine. I'm quite happy with that.

437
00:24:32.800 --> 00:24:36.120
And then Richard's left us to the interior to design ourselves.

438
00:24:36.200 --> 00:24:37.960
I think leopard skin and fluffy dice.

439
00:24:38.040 --> 00:24:39.640
That's nice. Maybe a chandelier.

440
00:24:39.720 --> 00:24:41.840
At the top. A nice crystal chandelier.

441
00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:43.560
Brilliant. What's wrong with that?

442
00:24:51.120 --> 00:24:53.280
Well. now the colour's chosen. That's good.

443
00:24:53.360 --> 00:24:56.040
But now it is down to us to get it show-ready.

444
00:24:56.120 --> 00:24:57.920
so it's gotta be good.

445
00:25:16.960 --> 00:25:19.120
We had an amazing reaction to the advert.

446
00:25:19.200 --> 00:25:22.120
and we have worked tirelessly to ensure that we've shortlisted

447
00:25:22.200 --> 00:25:24.440
the best candidates for Richard's business.

448
00:25:24.520 --> 00:25:26.480
So. the first one is mechanical?

449
00:25:26.560 --> 00:25:29.440
Yeah. Then we have a painter.

450
00:25:29.520 --> 00:25:31.120
Painter. right.

451
00:25:31.200 --> 00:25:35.160
The guys we're gonna meet today have a range of skills and experiences.

452
00:25:35.240 --> 00:25:38.480
At the end of today. Richard's gonna have some hard decisions to make.

453
00:25:38.560 --> 00:25:41.800
John or Jonathon? John will be fine. John. yeah.

454
00:25:41.880 --> 00:25:45.720
I just hope that I can go in there. I can do my best to impress Richard.

455
00:25:45.800 --> 00:25:48.800
and my experience and everything is just what he's looking for.

456
00:25:48.880 --> 00:25:50.720
and that's what gets me the job.

457
00:25:50.800 --> 00:25:53.160
John. Hello. mate. Pleasure.

458
00:25:53.240 --> 00:25:55.240
I'm Richard. Nice to see ya. Nice to meet ya.

459
00:25:55.320 --> 00:25:59.000
How are you at dealing with customers who insist on having

460
00:25:59.080 --> 00:26:01.680
their lovely old truck painted in a metallic blue.

461
00:26:01.760 --> 00:26:04.360
when you know full well it just won't work?

462
00:26:04.440 --> 00:26:07.040
Do you enjoy that? I try and dissuade them if you think

463
00:26:07.120 --> 00:26:10.080
it's probably not a matching fit. Yeah.

464
00:26:10.160 --> 00:26:15.040
Wayne has done a good job because. well. he whittled them down

465
00:26:15.120 --> 00:26:18.120
to candidates he thought were worth looking at. and they all are.

466
00:26:18.200 --> 00:26:19.800
Everyone I've met. they're good.

467
00:26:19.880 --> 00:26:23.040
What would be your biggest strength in this whole process?

468
00:26:23.120 --> 00:26:28.200
From here to it rolling out. painted. done. dressed. finished?

469
00:26:28.280 --> 00:26:30.000
I'm chuffed just to be shortlisted.

470
00:26:30.080 --> 00:26:34.200
I think there were quite a few applicants. and if I get the job. it'd be a dream come true.

471
00:26:34.280 --> 00:26:36.680
All right. well done.

472
00:26:36.760 --> 00:26:40.160
Thanks very much. I'll speak to you soon. Yeah. great. Cheers. Take care.

473
00:26:42.560 --> 00:26:45.720
I've gotta say. the whole filtering-them-down business worked.

474
00:26:45.800 --> 00:26:48.440
Thank you. So. it's now about deciding which.

475
00:26:50.120 --> 00:26:52.760
Is it two? Is it three?

476
00:27:04.120 --> 00:27:07.400
Ey up! F-100 pickup door? Yes.

477
00:27:07.480 --> 00:27:09.080
Oh. thank God. They're back.

478
00:27:09.160 --> 00:27:12.880
Right. now these were a complete mess. but he's done them.

479
00:27:12.960 --> 00:27:15.160
He's done a fantastic job.

480
00:27:15.240 --> 00:27:18.200
If you remember. there was nothing left at the bottom of the door.

481
00:27:18.280 --> 00:27:20.960
Oh. hello. No. it was completely... That was just lattice.

482
00:27:21.040 --> 00:27:22.640
There was nothing. No.

483
00:27:22.720 --> 00:27:24.920
Where's he pieced it in?

484
00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:27.680
Ooh. that is nice. isn't it? He's very clever.

485
00:27:27.760 --> 00:27:31.320
Ooh. that is satisfying. Good. 'cause that could have got us stuck.

486
00:27:31.400 --> 00:27:34.120
Brilliant. I'll crack on.

487
00:27:50.120 --> 00:27:54.200
Once we get new recruits and bring more skills to the Cog.

488
00:27:54.280 --> 00:27:57.800
the dream is for all our work to be on high-end projects.

489
00:27:57.880 --> 00:27:59.880
Hence. today's little outing.

490
00:28:02.120 --> 00:28:05.040
I'm off to look at a job. It's a car called a Kondor.

491
00:28:05.120 --> 00:28:07.600
It's currently owned by a lady called Kate.

492
00:28:07.680 --> 00:28:10.280
who is the daughter of. and it was the car of.

493
00:28:10.360 --> 00:28:12.720
a guy called Bryan Wingfield.

494
00:28:12.800 --> 00:28:15.480
which. if you're of a motoring persuasion.

495
00:28:15.560 --> 00:28:18.000
is a name that means something. He's a legend.

496
00:28:18.080 --> 00:28:21.240
Closely involved with the legendary Ford GT cars.

497
00:28:21.320 --> 00:28:23.720
three of which crossed the line together

498
00:28:23.800 --> 00:28:28.000
to win the 1966 Le Mans in an epic battle against Ferrari.

499
00:28:28.080 --> 00:28:30.360
There's been movies made about it. It's incredible.

500
00:28:31.880 --> 00:28:34.520
Bryan made this car himself

501
00:28:34.600 --> 00:28:36.960
and he wants to put it back on the road.

502
00:28:37.040 --> 00:28:40.200
I'm a little bit anxious. This is a one-off.

503
00:28:40.280 --> 00:28:43.960
and little old me is gonna go and have a look. Gulp.

504
00:28:51.200 --> 00:28:53.320
Kate. hello.

505
00:28:56.360 --> 00:28:57.960
Kate. Hello.

506
00:28:58.040 --> 00:29:01.200
Nice to see you. How are you? Lovely to meet you. Yeah. good.

507
00:29:01.280 --> 00:29:03.400
Is it in there? It is. it is.

508
00:29:03.480 --> 00:29:05.640
Good. good. I'll dip in and roll the doors up.

509
00:29:05.720 --> 00:29:08.560
Thank you. Let's just get straight to it. Yeah. absolutely.

510
00:29:29.160 --> 00:29:32.120
Can I? Absolutely.

511
00:29:33.120 --> 00:29:35.840
Oh. look at that. That's got presence.

512
00:29:39.840 --> 00:29:43.240
And there was only one of these. this one. There was only one. yeah.

513
00:29:43.320 --> 00:29:45.560
Although. Dad and the guys at Ford

514
00:29:45.640 --> 00:29:47.680
had developed the car and built the car.

515
00:29:47.760 --> 00:29:51.200
the whole thing just didn't get off the ground.

516
00:29:51.280 --> 00:29:54.160
So. let's just use this car

517
00:29:54.240 --> 00:29:56.720
to understand a bit more about your dad... Mm.

518
00:29:56.800 --> 00:29:59.000
...and what level of

519
00:29:59.080 --> 00:30:02.040
talent we're talking about here. Yeah. huge.

520
00:30:02.120 --> 00:30:04.600
I don't think you'll see another Bryan Wingfield.

521
00:30:04.680 --> 00:30:06.920
He could walk past any car and he'd go.

522
00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:09.280
"Rivets aren't right on that. They should be

523
00:30:09.360 --> 00:30:13.480
this many millimetres apart and they're not. They're. like. a millimetre out."

524
00:30:13.560 --> 00:30:17.160
But he'd say it very quietly. It wouldn't be...

525
00:30:17.240 --> 00:30:20.240
He was just so... He wasn't a pretentious man.

526
00:30:20.320 --> 00:30:23.480
He was the founder of the GT40 Owners Club.

527
00:30:23.560 --> 00:30:26.160
He knew every inch of the GT40.

528
00:30:26.240 --> 00:30:28.440
I'm very pleased that you've invited me along.

529
00:30:28.520 --> 00:30:31.200
What would you like us to do? What would you like back?

530
00:30:31.280 --> 00:30:36.560
A finished car. Dad was diagnosed with Alzheimer's 12. 13 years ago.

531
00:30:36.640 --> 00:30:40.880
The intention was. get it finished for him before he passed away.

532
00:30:40.960 --> 00:30:45.200
But. of course. he passed in March last year. and then that was it.

533
00:30:45.280 --> 00:30:47.440
Mark's an engineer. my husband. and he's very.

534
00:30:47.520 --> 00:30:49.160
very good. very. very capable.

535
00:30:49.240 --> 00:30:52.880
But even with Mark having done some bits and pieces with the rear brakes.

536
00:30:52.960 --> 00:30:56.000
he said the nostalgia that's there is.

537
00:30:56.080 --> 00:30:58.960
Bryan was the last one to undo these. and...

538
00:30:59.040 --> 00:31:01.640
Yeah. it's a real physical connection. It takes extra time.

539
00:31:01.720 --> 00:31:05.360
A real physical connection. He's struggling with it. I'm struggling with it.

540
00:31:05.440 --> 00:31:08.240
Totally understand that. So I think. with your blessing.

541
00:31:08.320 --> 00:31:12.160
what I'd love to do... is pull in some people.

542
00:31:12.240 --> 00:31:13.880
I don't think there's any doubt

543
00:31:13.960 --> 00:31:16.160
this needs to be something of a team effort.

544
00:31:16.240 --> 00:31:19.040
Ahead of this immensely deep scuttle.

545
00:31:19.120 --> 00:31:21.280
there isn't an engine under there at the moment?

546
00:31:21.360 --> 00:31:22.960
No. the engine is there. Right.

547
00:31:23.040 --> 00:31:26.000
That's the gearbox. So the mission is.

548
00:31:26.080 --> 00:31:28.240
all of those go in there.

549
00:31:28.320 --> 00:31:30.920
It's basically. Richard. like a big Meccano set.

550
00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:34.960
It is. apart from it's full size. incredibly unique.

551
00:31:35.040 --> 00:31:37.120
and unbelievably precious. Yes. Mm.

552
00:31:39.200 --> 00:31:42.520
That's a heck of a car. It's not just a car that you stand and look at.

553
00:31:42.600 --> 00:31:46.760
it's a car that you stand in the presence of. It has an aura.

554
00:31:46.840 --> 00:31:49.280
But here's my concern right now.

555
00:31:49.360 --> 00:31:52.840
we're at this level as engineers at The Smallest Cog.

556
00:31:52.920 --> 00:31:54.800
Bryan was up here.

557
00:31:54.880 --> 00:31:57.440
He could conceive. design. and build a race car.

558
00:31:58.280 --> 00:32:00.640
I need something to fill in some of this gap.

559
00:32:00.720 --> 00:32:03.360
This is where I look at where we might have shortfalls.

560
00:32:03.440 --> 00:32:05.840
and then I'll fill those gaps in.

561
00:32:30.160 --> 00:32:32.720
What the hell is going on?

562
00:32:34.680 --> 00:32:38.360
No power. There's just nothing at all. Nothing.

563
00:32:38.440 --> 00:32:42.600
Just about to paint the blue on the lower half of the F-100.

564
00:32:42.680 --> 00:32:46.000
I'll have to get it painted today so it gets built tomorrow for the show.

